Aye, I've started updating the SL thrust and ISP for those engines appropriately to make them next-to-useless while in deep atmo.

Still wish they would at least publish the numbers even if the engine would explode/be damaged by the instable flow.  If I had more patience I could probably calculate many of them given the chamber pressure, expansion ratio/areas, and vacuum stats... but that is a lot of rocket science that I don't want to take the time to learn.

 

In other news, have a basic implementation of boiloff availalble/working, and more importantly the tank-type modifiers now make (a bit more) sense:
Modifiers now effect the tankage volume loss, dry mass, costPerDryMass, impact tolerance, maxTemp/maxSkinTemp, and various boiloff parameters related to insulation type, quality, and EC cooling cost.

From top to bottom

Lightweight tank - lower tankage volume loss, lower dry mass, lower impact + heat tolerance, -more- boiloff from less insulation

Standard tank - the standard, default, generic...same old stuff you are used to, moderately insulated, uses default boiloff values

Low-Boiloff (passive) - passively insulated low-boiloff tank; does not require EC but has higher tankage volume loss and higher dry mass from added insulation, but prevents %50 of boiloff

Zero-Boiloff (active) - actively cooled zero-boiloff tank; spend EC to prevent boiloff, if EC not present it reverts to using an 'inactive' cooling value/percent.  higher tankage volume loss and dry mass than LBO tank due to added cooling mechanics.

Not Shown - structural tank; cannot hold any resources, but is strong and lightweight.

Not Shown/used - hybrid passive/active tank that derives 50% of its cooling amount from passive insulation and the remainder from active insulation when ec is available

 

 

Have implemented boiloff as a separate module that may -optionally- be patched onto any other fuel tanks you wish to support boiloff on; has minor integration with VolumeContainer to derive the boiloff stats, but otherwise uses its own config values if VC is not available.

Will work on a patch to setup some of that stuff and/or add VolumeContainer to the stock fuel tanks if RealFuels and/or MFT is not installed.

Need to decide how to handle interoperability between CryoFuels and SSTU (and/or others..); which mechanic should take precedence in those cases?  Would prefer, at least in my games, to use a single resource switch and boiloff mechanic across all parts (if possible).

 

Still a bit more stuff to cleanup on the VolumeContainer setup... but I'll likely start working on converting the rest of the parts (and modules) to use it a bit later today.  Seems to be pretty stable so far, and would rather make these breaking changes to the parts sooner than later.

If all goes well I'll likely have an updated release sometime tomorrow... perhaps later this evening if it goes really well

Yes, already implemented for all (most?) resizable parts.  Up to 1.25m diameter is available at the 'Start' tech node, 1.875m at the 45-science set of nodes, 2.5m at the 90-science set of nodes, 3.75m at the 300-science set of nodes, and full unlock (10m+) at the 550-science set of nodes (it is actually specific nodes but I'm too lazy to look up the names at the moment).  This should effect MFT, MUS, MSRB, PDC, RBDC, ISDC, IPA, FR, and MHS parts.  The only ones it -doesn't- effect are the engine cluster mounts; I allow those to be freely scaled as a large mount doesn't do you much good without a large tank above it.. so it is kind of self-limited by the tank tech-limitations.

If you are not seeing this while in career mode, please submit a bug-report as they are -supposed- to be tech-limited.
